Hey Everyone!

The  Hoodies  (Jan, Lena, Nick, Nolan)  were  just  at  JSConf   Budapest  this   week ! It   was an exciting event with lots of cool stuff happening!

# JSCON Budapest

Situated in Budapest, this year's JavaScript conference showcased plenty of workshops and engaging speakers.
Budapest is a city located on the Danube river. The capital consists of two cities, Buda and Pest.Budapest has been
reported as one of the best places to visit in Europe. As such it makes for a perfect place to  hold the JS conference.

#Speakers
1.LAURIE VOSS @seldo
Laurie talked about how  NPM  expects you to use NPM. He also talked about the commands and workflows that can make you better at NPM.
The talk can be found here :https://youtu.be/zWEU8kNKi3Q
2.Suz Hinton @noopat
Suze talked about  how Data creation, analysis, and corruption can be paired withJavaScript to discover new and improved things. The
talk can be found here: https://youtu.be/P8Cy2_ZHWI8
3.DENYS MISHUNOV @mishunov
Denys talked about the importance of performance in his talk. There are a lot of factors influencing performance  but Denys talked about the importance of perception.
Although the site may have few requests and be mathematically fast, it nonetheless may seem slow. He gives an interesting
speech on the how the user's perspective is the true measure of speed. Check it out here!
https://youtu.be/j9TrSkLZa5A?list=PL37ZVnwpeshE6PbF5GB4hvtU3A4HqMfxf
4. Yan Zhu @bcrypt
Yan talked about the importance of security and how it shouldn't be compromised for performance. Check it out here:
https://youtu.be/n9Fe68xgKUw?list=PL37ZVnwpeshE6PbF5GB4hvtU3A4HqMfxf
5.TimPietrusky @TimPietrusky/ MartinSchuhfuss @usefulthink
Tim and Martin put on a awesome audio/visual  performance with their skills in music,lights,MDI,and electronic.
Check it out here: https://youtu.be/KkV4alDBVhk
6.Lena Reinhard @lrnrd
Lena (our very own!!)  talks about how software plays an important role in peoples' everyday lives. She also dives into how you as a person can make a change in the tech industry.
You can listen to her talk here:
7. Sam Bellen
Sam decided to use the web-audio-api to change the sounds of his guitar . He talks  about how he accomplished this and showcases his skills.
Check it out here:https://youtu.be/BEdFcnI-ppk
8.Stefan Baumgartner @ddprrt
Stefan talks about the new version of HTTP and how it will affect the javascript developers of the future.
Watch his talk here: https://youtu.be/98z0XjYWX0o
9.Rachel  White @ohhoe
Rachel had a problem. Her cats kept waking her up at ungodly hours. So she built a web based feeder that is remote controlled!
In this talk she walks us through her learning process and how to submit it to open source community.
Watch it here: https://youtu.be/PTgqSpclwvE
10. Anand  Vemuri @brownhat57
Anand explains how cyber security breaches have occurred at the web application layer. In his talk anand talks about the less
frequently talked about vulnerabilities developed with javascript. Anand  will also go into how to prevent these vulnerabilities.
His talk can be seen here: https://youtu.be/qNmOUzxGg0Y
11.Claudia  Hernandez @koste4
Javascript has many interesting oddities and Claudia does a beautiful job of explaining them to us. This should help future and upcoming
developers avoid some upcoming headaches.
12.Rob Kerr @robrkerr
Rob is a neuroscientist who is also a web developer. He wants to bring the old ways of analyzing data and spread the resources to everyone!
Rob shows us the simulations of the electricity activity in our brain cells using javascript!
Watch it here: https://youtu.be/mz4N3U5f2tg
13.Nicolas  Bevacqua @nzgb
Nicolas also talks about web performance but in a different perspective! He does a great job explaining  about modifying CSS, and controlling TCP
delivery. Nicolas closes it off by talking about the upcoming HTTP 2.0and its new features!
14.Princiya Sequeira @princi_ya
Video games is a huge industry in todays world. We are getting more and more closer to virtual reality everyday! In this talk, Princiya  explains how
javascript can  be used to enhance our interaction and further progress video game technology.
15. Maurice Debeijer @mauricedb
Maurice gives us an interesting perspective on event sourcing our react-flux apps.Most react apps currently store the data  without change. However
using Event-Sourcing  with Command Query Responsibility Segregation (CQRS) is much more optimal.Maurice goes more into the detail of how the data is
stored  and how we can start using it for ourselves in our React apps.
16.Oliver Joseph Ash @OliverJAsh
What if we are working on an app and  we lose internet connection? In this talk Oliver explains using service workers to build an offline page for
theguardian.com . Working offline soon won't be an issue anymore!
17.Safia Abdalla  @captainsafia
Safia cracks some funny jokes and takes us on an adventure on memory management in javascript.Through this Safia tells us how we can implement code
better to improve performance and learn javascript concepts better.
Check out her interesting talk here: https://youtu.be/AeUCN2lPqL8
18. Nick Hehr @hipsterbrown
Last but not least our very own Nick does a fantastic job describing how the community is as important as the code. Its the people behind the project
that make it such an unique experience. Nick explains how fostering a community can  benefit the project and products.
Check it out here: https://youtu.be/kTuAQen5iTA

#Workshops
1. Nodebots
Users got to assemble, program and  battle bots! This was lead by Markus Leutwyler!
2.Journey towards Angular 2
In this workshop, Gabor and Andras walk through the migration process from  old school Angular JS to
more modern Angular. Users learnt to refactor the application to make migration easier!
3.Composing Music with Javascript
Andor Polgar uses Websockets and Web MIDI API to send musical notes to a synthesizer . He demonstrates how this can be used to control
any hardware with USB ports and decode MIDI messages.
4.Develop Webapps with Haxe
Balazs and Francis walk through using the Haxe language  using hexMachina MVC framework.
5.NodeSchool
Nodeschool teaches Node.js . Learn an important framework that can be used anywhere to implement apps.
6.Three.JS Viewer API
Jaime  and Adam  demonstrate setting up a node.js server and client side JS to create an interactive  website where 3D  model extensions
can be added!
7.Tessel-2
Nick is back in this one with Istvan as they showcase building a hardware project with Tessel-2. They demonstrate using javascript to
access the hardware  and build environmentally sensitive apps using web development skills.
8. Crash Course on Progressive Web Apps
Nolan demonstrates building fast mobile apps  with web technologies  using cutting edge APIs that works
well in all browsers.

